#Text=Henry
#Text=Porter ( playwright )
#Text=For other people named Henry Porter , see Henry Porter ( disambiguation ) .
#Text=Henry Porter ( died June 1599 ) was an English dramatist who is known for one surviving play , The Two Angry Women of Abington , and for the manner of his death .
#Text=He was stabbed by another playwright .
#Text=Life
#Text=Very little is known about Henry Porter 's life beyond the entries in the diary of Philip Henslowe the theatre manager .
#Text=He is described as a " gentleman " and a " poor scholar " , and as the play is set in Abingdon , near Oxford , and shows knowledge of the area around Oxford it is assumed he studied there .
#Text=Attempts to plausibly connect him with the records of the several Henry Porters at Oxford have been fruitless .
#Text=He is known for one surviving play , The Two Angry Women of Abington , first published in two editions in London in 1599 .
#Text=The Two Angry Women was written before his first recorded work for Henslowe in 1598 .
#Text=Porter was praised by Francis Meres in his Palladis Tamia in 1598 as one of " the best for Comedy amongst us " .
#Text=There is linguistic evidence that he may have contributed comic scenes to Dr. Faustus by Christopher Marlowe .
#Text=Works
#Text=The Two Angry Women of Abington has been compared favourably in style and quality to The Merry Wives of Windsor .
#Text=It is a rollicking country piece including two comic characters , Dick Coomes and Nicholas Proverbes , who are advertised in the title page of one original edition .

#Text=Henslowe records several payments in 1598 for the book and costumes for the play , but it must have been performed before 1599 , as there is a reference to these characters in Plaine Percevall , a pamphlet published that year in response to Martin Marprelate . [ 1 ]

#Text=Henslowe 's Diary mentions other plays , Love Prevented ( 1598 ) , Hot Anger soon Cold , with Henry Chettle and Ben Jonson ( 1598 ) , the second part of The Two Angry Women of Abingdon ( 1598 ) , The Four Merry Women of Abingdon ( 1599 ) , and The Spencers ( 1599 ) , with Chettle .
#Text=It is possible that " the second part of the Two Angry Women " was not a separate work , and it is not known whether the later plays were delivered before Porter 's death .
#Text=In 1598 Porter and Chettle were paid 20 shillings by Henslowe to write a play called The Second Part of Black Batman of the North .
#Text=It has been suggested that some of the money received from Henslowe by Porter was used to pay Chettle 's debts .
#Text=The considerable sums paid to Porter prove that his plays were popular , although the entries suggest he was unreliable .
#Text=Henslowe notes that the advance to Porter and Chettle was made after Porter " hath geven me his worde for the performance of the same and all so for my money " .
#Text=In February 1599 Henslowe acquired the sole rights of any play in which Porter had a hand , in return for a considerable advance of forty shillings .
#Text=Porter 's borrowings became more frequent , and the sums allowed less .
#Text=Death
#Text=It is likely that the publication of The Two Angry Women of Abington was prompted by Porter 's death .
#Text=The last definite record of him is an IOU in his hand in Henslowe 's diary on 26 May 1599 .
#Text=Leslie Hotson discovered the record of a case in the Southwark Assizes , which records the death of a Henry Porter on 7 June 1599 in Southwark .
#Text=He is recorded as having been struck a mortal wound in the left breast with a rapier " of the value of two shillings " the previous day . [ 2 ]

#Text=The killer is named as John Day , almost certainly the playwright of that name , who worked for Philip Henslowe . [ 3 ] Although collaboration was common there is no record of Porter and Day working together .
#Text=Ben Jonson , with whom Porter did collaborate , described Day as a " rogue " and a " base fellow " .
#Text=Day was charged with murder , but admitted manslaughter , on the grounds of self-defence , his plea in formal terms being that " he fled to a certain wall beyond which , etc " .
#Text=Although it is not recorded he seems to have obtained a Royal Pardon .
#Text=The rapier was a fashionable but particularly dangerous weapon , more likely to cause death than traditional swords .

#Text=It is ironic that one of the characters in The Two Angry Women laments " this poking fight of a rapier and dagger " saying that " a good sword-and-buckler man will be spitted like a cat or a coney " .
#Text=The irony would be greater still if the author of this was the same Henry Porter granted a " Pardon de se defendendo .
